AB  - We study the effects of natural disasters on labor time allocation and non-agricultural employment decisions for both men and women. Using microdata from China Family Panel Studies (CFPS), we apply Tobit and Heckman regression models to analyze how natural disasters reshape employment patterns. Our results reveal that natural disasters significantly reduce time allocated to agricultural work and increase time devoted to non-agricultural activities. Still, a substantial gender disparity emerges: women are less likely to transition into off-farm employment. This disparity stems from persistent gender roles, the burden of unpaid household labor and structural disadvantages in the labor market. These results highlight the need for gender-sensitive disaster recovery policies that mitigate inequalities and promote equitable labor outcomes.
