TI  - Reservoir operations for drought mitigation with dynamic hedging policy activated by drought limited water level and hedging coefficient intervals
T2  - JOURNAL OF HYDROLOGY
LA  - English
KW  - Drought mitigation
KW  - VMD-GBDT prediction model
KW  - Dynamic hedging policy
KW  - Multi-objective reservoir operation
KW  - DLWL and HC intervals
KW  - STORAGE
KW  - SYSTEM
KW  - RIVER
AB  - Frequent severe droughts have significantly unfavorable effects on agriculture and socio-economic development. It is crucial to derive the relationship between droughts and irrigation water demand and to explore effective reservoir operation strategies for mitigating drought impacts. In this paper, a novel integrated modeling framework was proposed to mitigate drought effects by coupling a Variational Mode Decomposition and Gradient Boosting Decision Tree (VMD-GBDT) prediction model for irrigation water demand forecasting, a multi-objective reservoir optimal operation model, and a dynamic hedging theory. The VMD-GBDT model was developed to simulate the irrigation water demand interval in response to various drought impacts. The drought limited water level (DLWL) intervals and hedging coefficient (HC) were simultaneously identified by incorporating a hedging policy into the multi-objective reservoir optimal operation model based on long-term historical hydrological information and irrigation water demand intervals. The DLWL is divided into multiple substages by the Fisher method. Then, the dynamic hedging policy of reservoir operation is activated by the staged DLWL and HC intervals when various droughts occur. The proposed framework was implemented to assess the performance of drought mitigation in the Baojixia Irrigation Area (BIA) of Northwest China. The results demonstrated a significant interrelation between irrigation water demand and meteorological, hydrological, and agricultural droughts. The dynamic hedging policy of reservoir operation activated by 3-stage DLWL and HC intervals was positive in mitigating the impacts of drought. In consecutive typical drought years, the maximum water shortage rate (WSR) declined 34.9%, the Linjiacun reservoir drought periods were shortened by 13.9%, and 91.7% of the standardized storage anomaly (SSA) was stable or elevated in the virtual aggregated reservoir. In a severe drought year, the mean WSR decreased by 4.00%, the standard deviation of WSR dropped by 7.70%, the SSA of Linjiacun reservoir increased by 50%, and the minimal SSA of the virtual aggregated reservoir increased by 73.3%. The results indicated that the proposed systematic modeling framework, "prediction of irrigation water-identification of DLWL and HC intervals-reservoir operation with dynamic hedging policy", is more effective at mitigating drought than the standard operating policy (SOP) and static hedging policy, providing a robust adaptive regulation approach during droughts.
